A digital approach to palaeography¶

Tesina for Mathematics in Machine Learning course by Michele Panariello

  1. Data exploration
  2. Outlier detection
  3. Baseline: LDA & QDA
  4. Support Vector Machines
  5. Logistic regression
  6. Ridge Classifier / Least Squares SVM
  7. K-Nearest-Neighbors
  8. Decision trees and random forests
  9. Final evaluation on test set
  10. References

We present an analysis of the Avila dataset, which contains features extracted from 800 images of the Avila Bible (Biblia de Ávila), a giant Latin copy of the Bible produced during the XII century between Italy and Spain (De Stefano, 2018).
Each record of the dataset containts 11 attributes pertaining to a group of 4 consecutive rows of the tome averaged together. We refer to each group of 4 rows as a pattern. The attributes of a pattern represent several palaeographic characteristics that were inferred from a digital scan of each page. Rubricated letters and miniatures were excluded from the scans.

The palaeographic analysis performed on the Avila Bible established that the manuscript contains pages written by 12 different scribe monks throughout the years. The goal of this analysis is to identify which scribe is the author of a certain pattern based on the available attributes. This makes the task a classification problem in which the copyist monk constitutes the class to predict.

To shorten computation times and to ease the illustation of the behavior of certain algorithms, we restrict our analysis to the patterns associated to 6 out of the 12 scribes. According to the available documentation, the attributes of dataset have already been standardized. A short description of the available attributes follows.

Attributes description¶

  • Page level features:
    • intercolumnar distance: distance between two columns of a page
    • upper margin: distance between upper margin of the page and first line of text
    • lower margin: distance between lower margin of the page and last line of text
  • Column level features:
    • exploitation: fraction of the column filled with ink. Formally computed as $N_{BP}(C)\,/\,N_P(C)$, where $N_{BP}(C)$ and $N_P(C)$ are the number of black pixels and the number of total pixels in the current column, respectively.
    • row number: number of rows in the current column
  • Row level features:
    • modular ratio: estimation of the dimension of the handwritten character
    • interlinear spacing: distance between two rows, in pixels
    • weight: fraction of row filled with ink. Analogous to exploitation, but for a single row
    • peak number: estimation of the number of characters in a row
    • modular ratio/ interlinear spacing: ratio of the two preceding attributes

All attributes are quantitative (i.e. numerical). The target variable is assigned the name monk; it is the only qualitative attribute of the dataset. Each copyist is denoted with a different letter.

Standardization¶

Standardization is a preprocessing technique that attempts to make the individual distributions of the attributes of the dataset more homogenous and comparable with one another.

Let $x_{ij}$ be the $j^{th}$ component of sample $\mathbf{x}_i$. Then we standardize it to $\tilde x_{ij}$ as follows:

$$\tilde x_{ij}=\frac{x_{ij}-\mu_j}{\sigma_j}$$

Where $\mu_j=\frac{1}{N}\sum_i{x_{ij}}$ and $\sigma_j=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N-1}\sum_i{(x_{ij}-\mu_j)^2}}$ are the mean and the standard deviation of the $j^{th}$ column, respectively.
Standardization ensures that no attribute of the dataset takes over all the others when computing distances between points: several algorithms, such as SVM and kNN, can greatly benefit from this.

Contrary to what is stated in the documentation, not all attributes are standardized. Most of the column means are reasonably close to zero; however, several standard deviations are above $1$, some going as high as $4.13$.

Boxplots¶

A boxplot can be described as a five-number summary of a univariate dataset. Such numbers are usually represented by graphical means as a shape similar to a box (hence the name boxplot) with two lateral bars called whiskers. The length of the bars roughly represents how "spread out" the data is.

The 5 points which summarize the data are computed as follows:

  • First quartile ($Q1$): the point below which lies 25% of the data points
  • Second quartile (median or $Q2$): the point below which lies 50% of the data points
  • Third quartile ($Q3$): the point below which lies 75% of the data points
  • Inter-Quartile Range $(IQR)$: computed as $Q3-Q1$
  • Maximum: computed as $Q3+\frac{3}{2}IQR$
  • Minimum computed as $Q1-\frac{3}{2}IQR$

It is worth remining that, contrary to what the name might suggest, maximum and minimum are NOT the maximum and the minimum points of the dataset in a strict mathematical sense. Instead, they are values that are employed to encompass the region where most of the points of the dataset should reasonably lie, under the assumption that they are centered around the mean.
Indeed, it is common practice to consider as outliers those points that lie outside the whiskers of the box.

Correlation matrix¶

A correlation matrix is a matrix which contains, for each possible couple of attributes $X$ and $Y$ in the dataset, the Pearson correlation coefficient between $X$ and $Y$, defined as

$$\rho_{X,Y}=\frac{Cov(X,Y)}{\sigma_{X}\sigma_{Y}}\in[-1,1]$$

Where $Cov(X,Y)=\frac{1}{N-1}\sum_{i}{(x_i-\mu_X)(y_i-\mu_Y)}$.

By graphically illustrating a correlation matrix in the form of an heatmap, it is possible to quickly assess whether some attributes of the dataset have very positive or very negative correlation.
A correlation close to $+1$ or $-1$ indicates that the two attributes $X$ and $Y$ behave as if they had some linear relationship of the kind $Y=cX$, with $c$ having the same sign of $\pm1$. However, said underlying relationship is not guaranteed to exist: this is often summarized with the statement correlation does not imply causation.

The correlation matrix reveals a high correlation between the attributes modular ratio and modular ratio/ interlinear spacing. This is reasonable, since the latter is just the former divided by interlinear spacing. According to (De Stefano, 2018), the attribute modular ratio/ interlinear spacing is misleading when trying to solve the clasifiction task using a MLP with 100 hidden neurons. We are not going to use any kind of neural network in this analysis, but we still remove the modular ratio/ interlinear spacing attribute because of its high correlation with modular ratio.

Other couples of features that ehxibit a remarkable correlation coefficient are:

  • weight and peak number ($0.516$). Intuitively, this is reasonable: recall that the former is the fraction of the row space occupied by the ink, and the latter is an estimation of the number of characters in a row. It makes sense to think that, if a row contains a lot of characters, then it will probably be more occupied by ink than the average.
  • intercolumnar distance and row number ($0.422$). From a purely intutitive standpoint, this correlation is likely to be spurious. We shall better asses this with a graphical comparison of the two attributes.

Pair plots¶

A pair plot is a set of graphs that illustrates all the possible pairs of predictors of a dataset plotted one against the other.
It can be used for a quick visual overview of how different attributes interact with each other.

In [16]:

pairpl._legend.remove()

The plot of the pair weight and peak number seems to confirm that there is some relationship of mutual growth between the two, which results in a fanning effect in the distribution of points.

On the other hand, there is no clearly visible linear relationship between intercolumnar distance and row number. Thus, the high correlation may be due to noise.

Noise actually seems to be one of the main problems of the dataset: several isolated points are visible in marginal positions of the graphs. Some of them tend to stretch out the range of the representation and do not allow a thorough visual inspection of the pair plots. We shall address this issue in the next section.

The following is concluded about the highly correlated attributes:

  • modular ratio/ interlinear spacing is removed
  • both intercolumnar distance and row number are kept
  • weight and peak number do seem to have some form of correlation, albeit not so critical. We choose to keep both the attributes for the moment, as most algorithms will likely not be hindered by this hint of collinearity. Nonetheless, it is worth to shortly delve into this issue for illustrative purposes.

Hazards of correlated attributes¶

Linear correlation between attributes (also referred to as multicollinearity) might consitute a problem mainly on certain kinds of linear models. In the area of classification, the term linear model usually indicates an algorithm that infers a vector of coefficients $\mathbf w$ and a bias term $b$ which can be used to linearly transform an input sample to obtain some score $f(\mathbf x)=\mathbf w^T\mathbf x+b$. This score can then be used to predict the label of the sample $\mathbf x$.

There are 3 main problems that could be caused by having strongly correlated attributes in the data:

  1. The computation of $(X^TX)^{-1}$ is numerically unstable. Inverting $X^TX$ is needed in some linear models that have a closed-form solution (e.g. linear regression). When perfect multicollinearity exists (i.e. when two predictors are actually linearly dependent) then $X^TX$ is not invertible.
  2. The trained model may have larger variance, i.e. give more different results for small variations of training data. This is because when one attribute changes, its correlated attribute changes too, making the estimation of the weights $w$ more "unstable".
  3. For the aforementioned reason, in linear models, tests regarding the $w$ coeffients may become less reliable.

That said, apart from the modular ratio/ interlinear spacing case, no correlation coefficient is overly high: thus, we are relatively safe from the illustrated issues.

Outlier detection¶

We now address the issue of the noisy observations within the dataset. In data analysis, there are two main practices related to the detection of data points with abnormal values:

  • Outlier detection: The training data contains outliers which are defined as observations that are far from most of the others. Outlier detectors try to enclose the region of data where relevant information lies, leaving out noise.
  • Novelty detection: an algorithm is trained on data that does NOT contain outliers. The algorithm must detect the presenct of novelties (i.e. abnormal observations) in data that it is given after the training step.

Before starting, we try to better visualize the distribution of each feature, divided by class.

def dataset_rug(data, labels, additional_title=None):
  """
  Displays one rug plot for each different feature of the dataset. Each rug is divided by label.

  Args:
    data (pandas DataFrame): the dataset to display
    labels (pandas series or np.array): labels of the dataset
    additional_title (str or None): string to display in brackets after main title. If None, nothing is shown.
  """
  n_rows = int(np.ceil(len(data.columns)/2).astype(int))
  row_col = [(i,j) for i in range(1, n_rows+1) for j in (1,2)][:len(data.columns)]
  title = f'[{len(data)} points]'
  if additional_title:
    title = additional_title + ' ' + title

  fig = make_subplots(
      rows=n_rows, cols=2,
      horizontal_spacing=0.03,
      vertical_spacing=0.1,
      subplot_titles=(data.columns)
  )

  fig.update_layout(
      margin=dict(t=50, b=25, r=20, l=20),
      showlegend=False,
      title={'text': title, 'x': 0.5, 'xanchor': 'center'},
      height=900
  )

  for column, (row, col) in zip(data.columns, row_col):
    fig.add_trace(
        go.Scatter(
            x=data[column],
            y=labels,
            mode='markers',
            marker=go.scatter.Marker(
              color=labels.cat.codes,
              symbol='line-ns-open',
              colorscale=['red', 'green', 'blue']
          )
        ),
        row=row,
        col=col
    )
  
  fig.show()

Isolation forest¶

Isolation Forest is an unsupervised outlier and anomaly detection algorithm introduced by (Liu, 2008) based on ensembles of data strctures called Isolation Trees (iTrees). The function of each tree is to try to isolate each point of the dataset by performing random splits on one feature at a time. We now describe how to construct an isolation tree and illustrate the workings of the algorithm.

1) iTrees¶

A tree is grown until it reaches some maximum depth or up to when its leaves contain one or zero samples. At each node of the tree, the data is recursively split on a random attribute, and on a random value within the range of that attribute.
Each iTree is trained on a subset $\psi$ of the complete dataset according to the following pseudocode:

iTree(X, e, l):
 // X=dataset, e=current tree height, l=height limit
 if e >= l or |x|<=1:
   return a terminal node
 else:
   randomly select and attribute q
   randomly select a value p in the range of q
   Xl <- {x ∈ X : x[q]<p}
   Xr <- {x ∈ X : x[q]>=p}
   return a node in which
     left child <- iTree(Xl, e+1, l)
     right child <- iTree(Xr, e+1, l)

$l$ is usually chosen as an estimation of the average height of a generic binary tree:

$$l=\lceil{\log_2{|\psi|}}\rceil$$

The size of $\psi$ recommended by the authors is $256$. We choose to leave it that way, since the original paper claims satisfactory results with it on both bigger and smaller datasets than Avila. Training iTrees on subsets of data rather than the whole dataset is helpful for two reasons:

  • it reduces memory usage.
  • if several outliers are clustered, they can be split up and be isolated by the trees more easiliy.

2) Training the ensemble¶

Any number of iTrees can be trained on subsets $\psi$ of the whole dataset, obtaining an Isolation Forest.

3) Outlier score¶

We can now compute an outlier score for any given sample $x$ based on the following principle: if, on average, it is possible to isolate $x$ with a low number of splits, then it is probably an outlier.

First, $x$ is passed through each iTree. The length of the path from the root to the leaf $x$ ended up in is computed as $h(x)$.

The outlier score of $x$ is:

$$s(x)=2\hat{}\left(-\frac{E(h(x))}{c(n)}\right)$$

where $c(n)=2H(n-1)-\frac{2(n-1)}{n}$ is a more precise estimation of the average height of an iTree for a dataset of $n$ instances. $H(i)\approx\ln(i)+0.577$.

The higher the score of a point is, the more likely it is to be an outlier.

  • $s(x)\approx 1$ indicates almost surely an outlier (since $E(h(x))\ll c(n)$)
  • $s(x)\approx 0.5$ means it took an average number of splits to isolate $x$ (since $E(h(x))\approx c(n)$), hence $x$ is not an outlier

Local Outlier Factor (LOF)¶

LOF is a density-based outlier detection algorithm proposed in (Breunig, 2000). It revolves around the concept of establishing a measure of "local density" of the space surronding a given data point. If a point $x$ has a lower local density than the average local density of its k-nearest neighbors, then it is probably an outlier.

We now introduce several concepts and metrics that lead to the definition of a local density measure. Let $p$ be a point in a feature space.

  1. We call $k\text{-}dist(p)$ the distance of $p$ from its $k^{th}$ nearest neighbor.
  2. We define $N_k(p)$ the set of points whose distance from $p$ is at most $k\text{-}dist(p)$. This is a broader definition of a set of k-nearest-neighbors: the set can contain more than $k$ points, if two of them are equally far from $p$.
$$N_k(p)=\{x:d(p,x)\leq k\text{-}dist(p)\}$$
  1. We define the k-reachability distance of $p$ as a metric that "pushes" a point $x$ away from $p$ to a distance of $k\text{-}dist(p)$, if $x$ was originally closer than that to $p$.
$$k\text{-}reach\text{-}dist(x,p)=\max \{ k\text{-}dist(p),\;d(x,p)\}$$

This is not a distance in the strict sense of the word, since it is asymmetrical. In particular, $k\text{-}reach\text{-}dist(x,p)$ will be equal to $d(x,p)$ if point $p$ is very crowded; however, if $p$ is isolated, $x$ will likely fall among its k-nearest neighbors, and will therefore be pushed away. Overall, one could say that $k\text{-}reach\text{-}dist(x,p)$ will grow larger than normal if $p$ is isolated.

With that in mind, we can state the following: given a point $A$ and its k-nearest neighbors $B_i\in N_k(p)$, a high average value of $k\text{-}reach\text{-}dist(A,B_i)$ indicates that $A$ is isolated.

  1. We define k-local reachability density of $A$ as the inverse of the average k-reachability distance of A from its k-nearest neighbors. If it is low, then the neighbors of $A$ tends to be isolated from its neighbors.
$$lrd_k(A)=\frac{|N_k(A)|}{\sum_{B\in N_k(A)}{k\text{-}reach\text{-}dist(A,B)}}$$

Finally, we can define the k-Local Density Factor of $A$ as the ratio between the average local density of the k-nearest neighbors of $A$ and the local density of $A$ itself.

$$LOF_k(A)=\frac{\sum_{B\in N_k(A)}{ldr_k(B)}/|N_k(A)|}{ldr_k(A)}$$

If $LOF_k(A)\gg 1$, then the neighbors of $A$ have a higher local density than $A$ itself, and $A$ is probably an outlier.

This techinque has one main problem: choosing the right hyperparameter $k$ is anything but easy. (Breunig, 2000) proposes a heuristic method whereby an upper and lower buond for $k$ is determined and all values of $LOF_k(x)$ are compared for $k\in [k_{max}, k_{min}]$. We follow a simpler approach and just leave the default $k$ parameter set by scikit-learn.

The last outlier detection methods we explore are SVM-based.

One-Class SVM and SVDD¶

Proposed by (Schölkopf, 1999), a One-Class SVM is an outlier and novelty detection algorithm which attempts to separate all data points of the dataset from the origin by following an approach similar to that of a classic Support Vector Machine (Vapnik, 1995).

The decision function which the algorithm tries to learn is of the form

$$f(x)=\text{sgn}(w^T\phi(x)-\rho)$$

which will return $+1$ for points on the side of the data cloud, and $-1$ for points closer to the origin. The goal is to find the hyperplane $w^T\phi(x)-\rho =0$ which best separates the dataset from the origin, while also:

  • minimizing $\|w\|$ for regularization
  • minimizing the values of slack variables
  • maximizing the intercept $\rho$

Therefore, the optimization problem of the One-Class SVM becomes

$$\min_{w,\,\xi_i,\,\rho}\frac{1}{2}\|w\|^2+\frac{1}{\nu N}\sum_{i=1}^N{\xi_i}-\rho$$$$\text{s.t.}\quad w^T\phi(x_i)\geq \rho -\xi_i\quad \text{and}\quad \xi_i\geq 0\quad \forall i=1\dots N$$

$\nu\in (0,1)$ is an hyperparameter. It is possible to prove that $\nu$ can be interpreted as an upper bound of the fraction of points in the training set that will be considered outliers by the algorithm. For example, if we expect that noise consitutes no more than $10\%$ of the data, we can set $\nu = 0.1$

Notice that, without slack variables, the first constraint would become $w^T\phi(x_i)- \rho\geq 0$, i.e. all points must be above the hyperplane.

Similarly to an ordinary SVM, the problem can be rewritten in dual form to obtain from the lagrange multipliers an $\alpha_i$ coefficient for each point: it will be nonzero only for support vectors. A more accurate description of the theoretical concepts underlying Support Vector Machines will be given later on.

Moreover, like all SVMs, One-Class SVM can be kernelized. In fact, wihtout kernelization, the algorithm is not really flexible and can be applied only to a limited range of scenarios.
Wihtout the use of a kernel, a similar, but more flexible option is constituted by the Support Vector Data Description (Tax, 2004).

A SVDD attempts to find the hypershpere of minimum radius which encloses all data points within it, while allowing some mistakes to reduce overfitting.
After the training stage, the points that lie outside the found hypersphere are considered outliers.

The optimization problem solved by the SVDD is:

$$\min_{R,\,a,\,\xi_i}R^2+C\sum_i{\xi_i}$$$$\text{s.t.}\quad \|\phi(x_i)-a\|^2\leq R^2+\xi_i \quad\text{and}\quad \xi_i\geq 0\quad\forall i$$

The resulting decision function returns $+1$ if the argument is within the found hypersphere, $-1$ otherwise. Again, it is possible to write the dual version of the above problem and kernelize the algorithm.

Interestingly enough, according to (Cherkassky, 2007), the formulations of One-Class SVM and SVDD become equivalent when using an RBF kernel. For the last outlier detection method, we will therefore use an RBF-kernelized One-Class SVM.
We set $\nu = 0.2$, so that we have again about $200$ outliers detected.

Additional observations and choice of outlier detection algorithm¶

By visually inspecting the attributes distribution, it is possible to see that some features seem to have some common "minimum value" (see intercolumnar distance, lower margin, row number). Several points, even coming from different classes, cluster around inidividual values, such as $-4.9222$ for row number.

We suspect that these values may be caused by the presence of some specially formatted pages to which the algorithm employed to digitalize the bible has reacted in the same manner, e.g. blank pages with 0 rows. In that regard, it might be reasonable to assume that the common low value of $-4.9222$ for row number might as well correspond to the number $0$, after having been standardized.

If we assume this is true, then there are two consequences:

  • the test data will likely have those extreme values too: it will be necessary to remove those outliers as well.
  • density-based methods such as LOF will be less effective in this scenario, since several points are clustered in those extreme values. Indeed, the rug plots seem to confirm that LOF is catching fewer of those marginal outliers.

Thus, we are left to choose between Isolation Forest and One-Class SVM. We select the former as outlier/novelty detection algorithm to employ in our pipeline, and move on to the nex step.

Baseline: LDA & QDA¶

We firstly use two simple models to obtain a baseline scoring. We do not apply any further processing to the data, for the moment.

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis is a classification techinque which makes use of Bayes' theorem to estimate the conditional probabiliy of the label $y$ given a set of features $x$.

$$P(y|x)=\frac{P(x|y)P(y)}{P(x)}$$

QDA consists in assuming that each probability $P(x|y=k)$ behaves as a multivariate normal with mean $\mu_k$ and variance-covariance matrix $\Sigma_k$. Formally,

$$P(x|y=k)=\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{d/2}|\Sigma_k|^{1/2}}\;\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}(x-\mu_k)^T\Sigma_k^{-1}(x-\mu_k)\right)$$

Where $d$ is the number of predictors and $|\Sigma_k|$ is the determinant of $\Sigma_k$.
By plugging the density of a multivariate normal in Bayes' formula and taking the $\log$, we obtain

$$\log P(y=k|x)=-\frac{1}{2}\log |\Sigma_k|-\frac{1}{2}(x-\mu_k)^T\Sigma_k^{-1}(x-\mu_k)+\log P(y=k)+P(x)$$

We can then assign to a sample $x$ the label $k$ which maximizes the expression above.

$$\hat y=\arg \max_k\big\{\log P(y=k|x)\,\big\}$$

$x$ appears in a quadratic form in $\log P(y=k|x)$, hence the name of the algorithm. Beacuse $P(x)$ is constant, it can be ignored in the maximization process.

By adding the further assumption that the covariance matrices are the same for all classes (i.e. $\Sigma_k=\Sigma\;\;\forall k$, a scenario known as homoscedasticity) the decision rule can be simplified to obtain a linear boundary (Hastie, 2009):

$$\hat y=\arg \max_k \left\{x^T\Sigma^{-1}\mu_k-\frac{1}{2}\mu_k^T\Sigma^{-1}\mu_k+\log P(y=k)\right\}$$

This variation of the algorithm is therefore called Linear Discriminant Analysis.

There is no pre-established rule to determine $P(y)$: it may be arbitrarly decided as a prior, depending on the available domain knowledge, or it can be inferred from the data. In scikit-learn, by default, $P(y=k)=N_k/N$, where $N_k$ is the number of samples belonging to class $k$ and $N$ is the dataset size.
Similarly, the real values of $\mu_k$ and $\Sigma_k$ will likely be unknown: one possible workaraound is to estimate them as the sample mean and the sample covariance matrix.

LDA and QDA are a very convenient way to set a baseline since they have no hyperparameters to tune, and they have been shown to work reasonably well with real data (not only perfectly gaussians distributions) (Hastie, 2009).

Nevertheless, to use LDA and QDA on the Avila dataset, we choose to drop two attributes that are evidently non-normal when conditioned on different labels: row number and interlinear spacing. This can be verified by inspecting the rug plot above, or by generating the QQ-plot of the quantiles of the two attributes against the quantiles of the normal distribution.

Q-Q plot¶

A Quantile-Quantile plot is a graphical way of comparing two probability distributions by plotting points $(x,y)$ so that $x$ and $y$ are the same quantiles from the two different distributions.
We can attempt to find out if a univariate dataset $X$ is approximately normally distributed by plotting its quantiles against those of a standard normal. If $X$ is normal (not necessarily standard), then the result should be a roughly straight line.

Holdout and cross-validation¶

We now need a quantitative method to tell whether the two aforementioned models are effective.

Holdout¶

Holdout is a simple technique which allows to validate the performance of a machine learning model on a given dataset.
When assessing the validity of an algorithm, the most naive option would be to split the available dataset in two parts: one to train the model, and one to validate the model for the prediction task. This practice is commonly known as holdout. If possible, the split should be carried out so that the class distribution is kept the same in training and validation set: this is known as stratified sampling.

Cross-validation¶

While the above approach is very simple and intuitive, it can yield a biased evaluation of the model, since the actual performance measurment was taken only on a subset of the data. One possible alternative is to use the $k$-fold cross validation techinque. It consists in the following:

  1. The dataset is partitioned into $k$ equally sized parts, possibly in a stratified fashion. These parts are called folds
  2. At the $k^{th}$ step, the model is trained on all but the $k^{th}$ fold, and then its performance measurment is taken on the $k^{th}$ fold.
  3. After $k$ steps, $k$ performance measurments have been obtained. They can now be summarized by means of any statistic, usually mean (and possibly standard deviation)

More specifically, given some gain function $G(y, \hat y)$, let $\hat {f}\,{}^{-k}(x)$ be an estimator fitted on all but the $k^{th}$ data fold. Then we can compute the cross validation score of the model as an average of the $k$ gain values:

$$CV(\hat f)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^NG(y_i,\hat{f}\,{}^{-\tau(i)}(x))$$

where $\tau(i):\{1,...,N\}\rightarrow\{1,...,K\}$ returns the fold of data that includes $x_i$.

If the analysis pipeline includes a pre-processing phase with multiple steps, then all these steps must be applied to each individual fold of the cross validation independently. In scikit-learn jargon, when applying transformers to the data, for each fold:

  • the transformer pipeline must be fit on the $k-1$ training folds (i.e. each transformer fits and then transforms the bulk of data composed of the $k-1$ training folds sequentially)
  • the transformer pipeline must only transform the validation fold (i.e. each transformer only transforms the validation fold sequentially)

In other words, the cross validation split must be applied upstream to any preprocessing: this means the transformation pipeline is applied $k$ times independently.

We run cross validation on both LDA and QDA to see which one performs better:

Evaluation metric choice¶

Once we have the predictions y_pred generated by a 5-fold cross validation, we can choose to apply different metrics on them. Let $TP=$ true positives, $TN=$ true negatives, $FP=$ false positives, $FN=$ false negatives. Then the following metrics can be defined:

Accuracy: $Acc=\frac{TP+TN}{TP+TN+FP+FN}=\frac{\text{correctly classified samples}}{\text{total samples}}$ (overall score, not related to a particular class)

Precision: $p(A)=\frac{TP}{TP+FP}=\frac{\text{items correctly predicted as A}}{\text{all items predicted as A}}$ (High precision → when model predicts A, the true class is likely to be A. But it may not be able to find all A's correctly)

Recall: $r(A)=\frac{TP}{TP+FN}=\frac{\text{items correctly predicted as A}}{\text{all items of true label A}}$ (High recall → model is likely to find all A's in the data, but it may also find a lot of non-A's)

F1-score: $f1(A)=\frac{2p(A)\cdot r(A)}{p(A)+r(A)}$ (the harmonic mean between precision and recall)

While accuracy is a global metric, the last three are computed on a specific class. One common choice to aggregate them is to use some kind of statistic of the f1-score:

  • Macro average: a normal average of the f1-scores for all classes. All $N_C$ classes count the same, regardless of their support.
$$f1_{macro}=\frac{1}{N_C}\sum_{i=1}^{N_C} f1(C_i)$$
  • Weighted average: an average weighted over the support $|C_i|$ of each class. Less populated classes will be less taken into account.
$$f1_{weight}=\frac{1}{N_C}\sum_{i=1}^{N_C}\frac{|C_i|}{N_{data}}f1(C_i)$$
  • Micro-average: we first compute micro-average of precision and recall. They are the normal precision and recall measures, but computed on the overall true positives, false positives and false negatives, rather than those of a specific class.
$$p_{micro}=\frac{TP_{tot}}{TP_{tot}+FP_{tot}}\quad\quad r_{micro}=\frac{TP_{tot}}{TP_{tot}+FN_{tot}}\quad\quad f1_{micro}=\frac{2p_{micro}\cdot r_{micro}}{p_{micro}+r_{micro}}$$

It can be shown that, in classification tasks in which every test case is is assigned to exactly one class, micro-f1 is equivalent to accuracy.

The metric choice is highly dependent on the task. In general, a micro average will evaluate the performance of the model regardless of how it interacts with each class; on the other hand, a macro average will make sure that all classes are equally considered by the algorithm. This can be useful in cases of highly unbalanced datasets, where the model might have a much higher performance on the majority class.
For example, if we are modeling some rare disease that is found in a small fraction of the population, we may want to evaluate it based on a macro-averaged metric in order to better recognize the occurrences of that disease.

In our scenario, we assume that no scribe is more relevant than another: therefore, we simply aim to maximize the general performance of our model. Of course, any paleography expert would have the right to disagree on such an assumption and rectify it as needed; and we would certainly heed his advice and select a more suitable metric for the task at hand. However, in the lack of a domain expert to guide our analysis, we simply follow our intuition on what may be the most reasonable choice.
Thus, we choose accuracy as evaluation metric, which in our case is equivalent to a micro-averaged f1. That is, we choose not to force the model to equally consider all copyist monks, but we aim to maximize the algorithm's overall predictive power.

    ax_dbar[0].invert_xaxis()

    ax_dbar[0].set_yticklabels([])
    ax_dbar[1].set_yticklabels(results.index)
    ax_dbar[1].set_yticks(np.arange(len(results)))

    ax_dbar[0].xaxis.get_major_ticks()[0].label1.set_visible(False)

    ax_dbar[0].set_xlabel('N. items')
    ax_dbar[1].set_xlabel('f1-score')
    fig_dbar.suptitle(title);

Support Vector Machines¶

The first model we analyze are Support Vector Machines (SVMs), originally introduced as a binary classification algorithm (Vapnik, 1995). We will later see how to extend such algorithm to a multiclass scenario.
SVMs generate decision functions that belong to the hypothesis class of halfspaces: that is, they attempt to infer an $n$-dimensional hyperplane of the form $w^Tx+b=0$ which will separate the samples of the two classes within the feature space. Assuming w.l.g. that the labels take on the values $\pm 1$, the decision function associated to an halfspace can be expressed as:

$$f(x)=\text{sgn}(w^Tx+b)$$

Assuming that a separating hyperplane does exist, given a training set of points $TS=\{(x_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^N$, we want the algorithm to find $w$ and $b$ such that $\text{sgn}(w^Tx_i+b)=y_i\,\,\forall i$, i.e. all points are correctly classified. Such condition can be equivalently formulated as

$$y_i(w^Tx_i+b)>0\quad\forall i$$

This general premise can be applied to all algorithms that generate halfspace decision functions. We will now describe how SVMs perform the inference of $w$ and $b$.

Hard margin SVM¶

In the Hard margin SVM formulation, we assume the realizability of the hypothesis, i.e. there exists an hyperplane that perfectly separates the two classes and for which the aforementioned bound applies. Then a hard margin SVM attempts to find an hyperplane which:

  1. Results in correct classification of all points
  2. Maximizes the distance between the hyperplane itself and the points of any class that are closest to it. The distance between such point and the hyperplane is called margin.

Recall that the distance of a generic point $x_i$ from a hyperplane $w^Tx+b=0$ can be expressed as

$$d(x_i)=\frac{\|w^Tx_i-w^Tx\|}{\|w\|}=\frac{\|w^Tx_i+b\|}{\|w\|}=\frac{y_i(w^Tx_i+b)}{\|w\|}$$

Which becomes $d(x_i)=y_i(w^Tx_i+b)$ with the additional assumption that $w$ is of unit norm.
Therefore, the measure of the margin can be expressed with $\text{margin}=\min_i d(x_i)=\min_i y_i(w^Tx_i+b)$. The above two points can then be mathematically formulated as a constrained optimization problem:

$$(w_0, b_0)=\underset{w,\,b\,:\,\|w\|=1}{\operatorname{argmax}}\{\min_i y_i(w^Tx_i+b)\}$$$$\text{s.t.}\quad y_i(w^Tx_i+b)>0\,\;\;\forall i$$

Now let $\gamma$ be the (still unknown) value of the margin. By setting $w':=w\,/\,\gamma$ and $b':=b\,/\,\gamma$, we can then re-write:

  • the margin as $1\,/\,\|w'\|$
  • the constraint as $y_i(w'^Tx_i+b)\geq 1$

Which yields the classic formulation of the hard margin SVM problem:

$$(\hat w, \hat b)=\underset{w',\,b'}{\operatorname{argmin}}\frac{1}{2}\|w'\|^2$$$$\text{s.t.}\quad y_i(w'^Tx_i+b')\geq 1\;\;\forall i$$

where the original $w_0$ and $b_0$ we sought are $w_0=\hat w\,/\,\|\hat w\|$ and $b_0=\hat b\,/\,\|\hat w\|$.

This formulation of the SVM problem is unrealistic and not very flexible, since it relies on the assumption that data points are linearly separable. Because this is often not the case, this requirment is often relaxed in an alternative formulation of the SVM.

Soft margin SVM¶

The separability assumption is relaxed in the so-called soft margin SVM, in which the model is allowed to "make mistakes": some data points can now cross the the hyperplane that the hard margin algorithm would find, and thus be misclassified. This makes the model less sensible to noise and can dramatically improve performances, so much that this version of the SVM has practically become the standard in real use-cases.

The relaxation of the correct classification bound is carried out by introducing the so called slack variables $\xi_i$ to the constraint.

$$y_i(w^Tx_i+b)\geq 1-\xi_i\quad\forall i$$

Each point is associated to one slack variable which measures how much that point is violating the hard margin rule. If the point is not crossing its margin, then its slack variable is $0$. In other words, a slack variable can be seen as a contribution of a hinge loss:

$$\xi_i=\max(0,\;1-y_i(w^Tx_i+b))$$

Thus, it is possible to formulate the new soft-margin optimization problem as

$$\min_{w,\,b,\,\xi}\frac{1}{2}\|w\|^2+C\sum_{i=1}^N\xi_i$$$$s.t.\quad y_i(w^Tx_i+b)\geq 1-\xi_i\quad \text{and}\quad \xi_i\geq 0\;\forall i$$

where $C$ is an hyperparameter which controls the degree to which the slack variables are taken into account when minimizing the objective function. For a high $C$, the algorithm will be stricter and will allow fewer mistakes.
For $C\rightarrow\infty$, we again obtain the hard margin SVM.

The soft margin SVM is more flexible than its hard margin counterpart: it is no chance that the minimization problem above could be seen as a combination of a hinge loss and a L2 regularization term:

$$(\hat w, \hat b)=\arg\min_{w,\,b}\lambda \|w\|^2+\rm R_s^{hinge}(h)$$

where $R_s^{hinge}(h)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N \max(0,\;1-y_i(w^Tx_i+b))$. Indeed, the goal of a regularization term is to find a good tradeoff between model complexity and classification performance: this has the effect of reducing overfitting, which is exactly what the soft margin does with respect to the hard margin.

Hyperparameter tuning¶

We have now introduced a new hyperparameter $C$, for which we must find the most suitable value. This operation is often called tuning. In general, any parameter $\alpha$ of any model $f(x,\alpha)$ can be tuned through cross-validation by finding $\hat\alpha$ which maximizes the score obtained with cross-validation:

$$\hat\alpha=\arg\max_\alpha\;CV(f, \alpha)=\arg\max_\alpha\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^NG(y_i,f^{-\tau(i)}\left(x, \alpha)\right)$$

Extending SVM to the multiclass case¶

So far, SVM was described as a binary classification algorithm; however, our dataset has more than just two classes.
There are two ways SVM is commonly extended to a multiclass model: we briefly discuss them below. These methods are not specific to SVMs and can theoretically be applied to other halfspace binary classifiers.

1. One vs Rest (OvR)¶

For each label $i$, we train a binary classifier and obtain a decision function $f_i(x)=w^Tx+b$ which must distinguish instances of class $i$ from instances of all other classes.
The numerical value of $f_i(x)$ is higher if point $x$ is farther away from the plane, in the $+1$ side: thus, we can interpret the output of $f_i(x)$ as a "certainty measurement" from the classifier that $x$ belongs to class $i$. The natural choice is then to assign to $x$ the label $i$ whose decision function returns the highest value:

$$f_{\text{OvR}}(x)=\arg\max_{i\in Y} f_i(x)$$

2. One vs One (OvO)¶

We train a classifier for each possible couple of classes: we obtain $f_i(x)$ which is supposed to distinguish between those two classes only. To classify point $x$, we pass it through all classifiers. We then perform a majority vote: the class that gets predicted the most is assigned to $x$.

In scikit-learn, the class LinearSVC implements a One vs Rest strategy for multiclass classification, while the class SVC implements a One vs One strategy. We will use both in our validation procedure and compare their performance.
Further differences between LinearSVC and SVC involve kernelization options, which will be discussed in the following section.

def gridsearch_or_load(gs, X, y, path):
    """
    Check if the given path exixts. If so, read result file of the gridsearch from memory.
    Otherwise, run the gridsearch and save the results in memory.
    
    Args:
        gs: sk-learn gridsearch instance
        X: training data
        y: target
        path: path of the result file
    
    Returns:
        gs estimator passed
        result pandas dataframe
    """
    if exists(path):
        res = pd.read_csv(path)
        print('Read result from memory')
    else:
        print('Launching gridsearch...')
        gs.fit(X, y)
        res = pd.DataFrame(gs.cv_results_)
        res.to_csv(path, index=False)
        print(f'Results stored at {path}')
        
    return gs, res

Kernelizing the SVM¶

As previously mentioned, an SVM algorithm results in a decision function of the form of an halfspace.
This can be particularly effective for high-dimensional spaces, in which points tend to be more sparse, and it is therefore somewhat "easier" to find an hyperplane that separates them.

However, the data might be distributed in such a way that it is impossible to find a linear separation between classes. One possible solution is to project the data $X$ into a higher dimensional space in which we hope it is possible to find a linear separation between classes.
This strategy is not exclusive to SVM: in principle, it can be applied to any dataset, regardless of the algorithm. One general procedure for that would be:

  1. Choose some mapping function $\phi : \mathcal{X}\rightarrow \mathcal{F}$, where $\mathcal{X}$ is the original space and $\mathcal{F}$ is the new feature space of higher dimension. One possible example could be $\phi : x\mapsto(x, x^2)$
  2. Given a training set $S=\{(x_i,y_i)\}_i$, compute the mapped dataset $\hat S=\{(\phi(x_i),y_i)\}_i$
  3. Train a linear model over $\hat S$, to obtain a classification function $f$. At test time, for point $x$, compute $f(\phi(x))$

However, this procedure may be computationally unfeasible: if the starting data is already high-dimensional, then projecting it into another space might be too costly in terms of memory, time, or both.
Nevertheless, for certain algorithms, it is possible to circumvent this issue by making use of the so-called kernel trick. The SVM is one of those algorithms.

A kernel function represents an inner product in a higher-dimensional space. It is a way to implicitly project points to higher dimensions without actually computing the mapping.

$$K(x,x'):=\langle\phi(x),\phi(x')\rangle$$

This means that, if it is possible to express a certain algorithm only in terms of inner products $\langle x,x'\rangle$, then we can implicitly project every processed point by substituting $\langle x,x'\rangle\rightarrow K(x,x')$.
A formulation of the SVM which only depends on inner products can be found by computing the dual optimization problem. This is achieved by taking the Lagrangian of the original objective function and setting its gradient to $0$. Some algebric manipulation then leads to the following forumlation of the dual problem:

$$\min_{\alpha}\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^N\sum_{j=1}^N y_i y_j \alpha_i \alpha_j \langle x_i, x_j\rangle-\sum_{i=1}^N \alpha_i$$$$s.t.\quad 0\leq\alpha_i\leq C\;\;\forall i\quad \text{and}\quad\sum_{i=1}^N y_i\alpha_i=0$$

where $\alpha_i$ are the Lagrange multipliers associated to the first contraint of the soft margin primal. It can also be shown that the original (and optimal) $\hat w$ and $\hat b$ term can be expressed in terms of Lagrange multipliers:

$$\hat w=\sum_{i=1}^N\alpha_i y_i x_i\quad\quad\hat b=y_{sv}-\langle\hat w,x_{sv}\rangle$$

where $x_{sv}$ and $y_{sv}$ are any support vector and its associated label, respectively (more about support vectors shortly).

Notably, one could also prove the following:

  • for correctly classified vectors that lie outside the margin (i.e. $x_i$ for which $y_i(\langle \hat w,x_i\rangle+\hat b)>1$) $\;\Longrightarrow\;\alpha_i = 0$
  • for vectors that lie exactly on the margin (i.e. $x_i$ for which $y_i(\langle \hat w,x_i\rangle+\hat b)=1$) $\;\Longrightarrow\;0<\alpha_i < C$
  • for vectors that lie within the margin and for misclassified vectors (i.e. $x_i$ for which $y_i(\langle \hat w,x_i\rangle+\hat b)<1$) $\;\Longrightarrow\;\alpha_i = C$

Therefore, only misclassfied data points or points that lie exactly on the margin give an actual contribution to the sum $\hat w=\sum_{i=1}^N\alpha_i y_i x_i$. Hence the name of the algorithm: the parameter $w$ of the optimal separating hyperplane is given by a sum of vectors that "support" the margin.

Back to kernels: we can now express the whole SVM algorithm only in terms of inner products between data points.
The ojbective function to minimize becomes:

$$\min_{\alpha}\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^N\sum_{j=1}^N y_i y_j \alpha_i \alpha_j K(x_i, x_j)-\sum_{i=1}^N \alpha_i$$

While the decision function can now be expressed as: $$f(x)=\langle \hat w,x\rangle+\hat b=\langle\sum_{i=1}^N\alpha_i y_i x_i, x\rangle+\hat b=\sum_{i=1}^N\alpha_i y_i\langle x_i,x\rangle+\hat b$$

in which we can again substitute the kernel

$$f(x)=\sum_{i=1}^N\alpha_i y_i K(x_i,x)+\hat b$$

Popular kernel choices include:

  • radial basis function (RBF) kernel: $K(x, x')=\exp(\gamma \|x-x'\|^2)$
  • polynomial kernel: $K(x,x')=(\gamma \langle x, x'\rangle + r)^d$
  • sigmoid kernel: $K(x,x')=\tanh(\gamma \langle x,x'\rangle + r)$

Notice that the above are kernel functions and not the mappings $\phi(\cdot)$ themselves. However, we have a way to know these undoubtedly correspond to some underlying mapping function thanks to Mercer's theorem.

Mercer's theorem. Let $K:\mathcal{X}\,\text{x}\,\mathcal{X}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$ be a symmetric and positive semi-definite function. Then $K$ implements an inner product $\langle\phi(x),\phi(x')\rangle$ in some hilbert space.
A kernel function is said to be positive semi-definite if either of the following (equivalent) condition is true:

  • $K$ is square-integrable (or "$L_2$") in $\mathcal{X}\,\text{x}\,\mathcal{X}$ and satisfies $$\int_{\mathcal{X}\,\text{x}\,\mathcal{X}}K(x,x')f(x)f(x')dxdx'\geq 0\quad\forall f\in L_2(\mathcal{X})$$
  • $K$'s Graham matrix $G_{ij}=K(x_i,x_j)$ is positive semi-definite $\forall x_1\dots x_m$ (i.e. $x^TGx\geq 0\;\;\forall x$).

In our analysis, we will experiment with all presented kernels. The RBF kernel introduces a new parameter to tune, $\gamma$; the polynomial kernel introduces two more, $d$ (the polynomial's degree) and $r$ (the intercept). Beacuse our computational resources are limited, we will only tune $\gamma$ and $d$ and leave $r$ at default setting.

def one_result_line_svc(res, label, title, ax):
    """
    Plots an errorbar plot to the given axis using the data contained in res. The output is assume to be the one of an SVM and is plotted across the C values.
    
    Params:
        res (pandas DataFrame): result of a GridSearchCV instance
        label (str): label to show in the legend
        title (str): title of the axis
        ax (plt axis): axis to plot on
    """
    ax.set_xscale('log')
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.grid(True)
    
    ax.errorbar(x=res['param_svc__C'], y=res['mean_test_score'], yerr=res['std_test_score'], label=label)
    
    # Annotating the maximum value (assuming there is one. Let's be serious, there won't be two)
    max_record = res.loc[res['mean_test_score'].idxmax()]
    xp = max_record['param_svc__C']
    yp = max_record['mean_test_score']
    text = round(max_record['mean_test_score'], 2)
    ax.annotate(text=text, xy=(xp,yp))

    ax.legend()
    ax.set_xlabel('C')

        one_result_line_svc(data, f'gamma={gamma}', title, ax)

Logistic regression¶

We had little succcess in trying to model the class distribution of the dataset with a linear kernel SVM. We now move towards a completely different kind of linear model and see wether this brings us to the same conclusion.
Despite its name, the logistic regression model is a classification technique. The name "regression" might stem from the fact that this algorithm can be described as a part of the wider framework of Genralized linear models. We firstly describe the mathematical formulation of logistic regression for binary classification problems; we then give a brief intuition on how this technique can be extended to the multiclass case.

In a Generalized linear model, we model $\mathbb{P}(y|x,w)$ as some distribution belonging to the exponential family. According to the kind of response $y$ we can get, we choose a suitable distribution for $\mathbb{P}(y|x,w)$.
Such choice affects the possible values taken on by $\mathbb{E}(y)$, which is what we primarily try to describe in a generalized linear model. The most general form of a generalized linear model is:

$$\mathbb{E}(y)=g^{-1}\left(Xw\right)$$

where $g^{-1}$ is the inverse of the so-called link function. In short, we are trying to mathematically model the expected value of the response with a linear combination of predictors $Xw$ passed through a suitable function $g^{-1}$. The role of such function is primarily to map the image of $Xw$ (which spans through all the real numbers) to the domain of $\mathbb{E}(y)$ .

In a logistic regression model, we assume that the response variable is binary and behaves like a Bernoulli random variable with parameter $p$. In other words, $y_i$ can either be $1$ or $0$ with probability $p_i$ and $1-p_i$ respectively, and $\mathbb{P}(y_i|p_i)=p_i^{y_i}(1-p_i)^{1-y_i}$. Consequently, $\mathbb{E}(y_i)=p_i\in [0,1]$. The inverse of the link function must be of the kind $g^{-1}:(-\infty, +\infty)\longrightarrow [0,1]$. One common choice, which can be motivated by theoretical aspects not discussed here, is the "logistic function":

$$\mathbb{E}(y_i)=p_i=g^{-1}\left(w^Tx_i\right)=\frac{e^{w^Tx_i}}{1+e^{w^Tx_i}}$$

which implies that the link function is the logit function $g(p)=\ln (\frac{p}{1-p})=w^Tx_i$. Which means the probability mass of $y$ is modeled as

$$P(y_i|x_i,w)=\left(\frac{e^{w^Tx_i}}{1+e^{w^Tx_i}}\right)^{y_i}\left(1-\frac{e^{w^Tx_i}}{1+e^{w^Tx_i}}\right)^{1-y_i}$$

The parameter $w$ can then be estimated by maximum likelihood. However, the equation $\frac{d}{dw}L\left(w|X,y\right)=0$ does not have a closed form solution, so an optimal value for $w$ must be computed by means of numerical optimization techniques.
Below is a graphical representation of the logistic function.

In simpler terms, logistic regression models the log-odds of sample $y_i$ belonging to class $1$ as a linear combination of predictors $x_i^Tw$.

As previously mentioned, the method described above is valid for binary classification problems. In order to expand logistic regression to the multiclass scenario, the following options can be considered:

  • choose another suitable link function so that it adapts to multiple possible values of $y$. The details are not discussed here, but the idea is to use $K-1$ logits as links, thus estimating $(p+1)\times(K-1)$ parameters (where $p$ is the number of predictors and $K$ the number of classes). This results in a density of $P(y_i=k|\mathbf{x}_i,\mathbf{w}_k)$ that resembles a softmax function.
  • use the One vs Rest or One vs One approach as previously described.

The scikit-learn library offers both implementations. We are going to employ the former, as it is the default setting for multiclass problems.

While classes A, I and X are very well recognized by the model (despite X being the least numerous), labels F, E and H seem harder to classify. One possible targeted countermeasure would be to try to make these classes more recognizable. We adopt a strategy based on oversampling: we will try to generate synthetic examples of classes F, E and H to make them more numerous, hoping that this will assist the model in better recognizing them. Of course, to carry out such a task, we need an oversampling algorithm.

Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique (SMOTE)¶

SMOTE is an oversamplig technique proposed in (Chawla, 2002) to tackle the problem of class imbalance in a training dataset for a classification task. It essentially consists in tracing "hyper-segments" between points of a minority class, then sample new synthetic points along those segments. The following pseudo-code illustrates this mechanic more in depth:

SMOTE(D, k, N):
    // D: unbalanced dataset, k: number of neighbors, N: final size of minority class
    while the minority class has fewer than N points do:
        A <- random point within the minority class
        B <- random point within the k nearest neighbors of A of its same class
        for attr in each attribute of the feature space:
            λ <- random number ∈ (0,1)
            new_point[attr] <- A[attr] + (B[attr]-A[attr])*λ
        add new_point in minority class

This algorithm can be used to artificially incerase the instances of a certain class to some number $N$ until the desired balance is achieved.

We will use SMOTE on classes F, E and H to make them more numerous: hopefully, this will make the model more aware of their presence and will ease their classification.

Cross validation and SMOTE¶

When using cross validation, one must make sure that only the training folds are oversampled, and not the validation fold. This means that it will be necessary to run SMOTE $k$ times, where $k$ is the number of folds.
It is equally important to make sure that the sampling for the partitioning is stratified, so that the original distribution of the classes is kept the same in all folds. This is a general rule which holds even when not applying SMOTE.

In the following code, we address both of those matters. We attempt to find the best oversampling proportions by trial and error; the final sampling strategy can be found in the code.

def smote_cross_val(clf, smote, X, y, cv=5):
    """
    Performs cross-validation by using SMOTE.
    
    Params:
        clf: sklearn classifier
        smote: imblearn instance of a smote class
        X: traning data, not oversampled
        y: labels, not oversampled
        cv: number of folds
        
    Returns:
        statistics of f1 and accuracy for each fold aggregated as a pd DataFrame
    """
    skfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=n_folds)
    stats = pd.DataFrame(columns=list(y.cat.categories)+['accuracy'])

    for train_index, val_index in skfold.split(X, y):
        X_train, X_val = X.iloc[train_index], X.iloc[val_index]
        y_train, y_val = y.iloc[train_index], y.iloc[val_index]

        # Resample only the current training data with smote
        X_train_r, y_train_r = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

        clf.fit(X_train_r, y_train_r)
        y_pred = clf.predict(X_val)

        f1s = f1_score(y_val, y_pred, average=None)

        new_row = {label: f1 for label, f1 in zip(y.cat.categories, f1s)}
        new_row['accuracy'] = accuracy_score(y_val, y_pred)
        stats = stats.append(new_row, ignore_index=True)
    
    return stats

We therefore recap some existing variations on the original SMOTE algorithm, to see whether some slightly more advanced oversampling technique can be helpful.

SVM-SMOTE¶

Proposed in (Nguyen, 2009), this technique combines an SVM classifier (possibly kernelized) with SMOTE oversampling. We first run the SVM algorithm on the original (i.e. not oversampled) dataset and obtain some support vectors. The idea is that, because support vectors are those that are closest to the boundaries between classes, they may aid in distinguishing class clusters.
Therefore, for the classes we intend to oversample, we select the support vectors whose $k$-nearest neighbors are mostly from the same class. We then run SMOTE on those points.
This should results in a more clearly outlined border between classes, which could in turn ease the classification task for the model.

Notice that distances between points be computed in kernel space with the formula

$$d\left(x,x'\right)=\sqrt{K\left(x',x'\right)+K\left(x,x\right)-2K\left(x, x'\right)}$$

K-means SMOTE¶

(Last, 2017) proposes a techinque based on running a K-means algorithm on the data prior to oversampling. Among the K found clusters, we then pick the ones whose samples mostly come from the minority class, and only run SMOTE within those. This should avoid tracing hypersegments which overlap with the bigger clusters of majority samples.

ADASYN¶

For each point in the minority class, we compute the $k$-nearest neighbor. We then compute the fraction of samples from the majority class amongst those $k$ neighbors: the oversampling will be performed more heavily for points whose neighbors are mostly from the majority class. Hence the name ADASYN: adaptive synthetic sampling (Haibo, 2009).

Let us recall that, in the previous section, we have established that an SVM with an RBF kernel works rather well on this dataset; moreover, we already have run a grid search with said classifier and obtained the best parameters for the task. Therefore, we make an attempt at using SVM-SMOTE to see if that brings any additional improvement over traditional SMOTE. The SVM we use for the initial step is run with the best hyperparameters found at the end of the previous section.

Akaike information criterion (AIC)¶

We want to verify is it is helpful to remove some attribute which might mislead the model. To do so, we use a model selection technique known as AIC.

Akaike information criterion (AIC) (Akaike, 1974) can be used to assess the validity of models which use a maximum likelihood approach to infer their parameters from the available data. Let $k$ be the number of predictors used by the model and $L_{\text{MLE}}$ be the likelihood of its parameters. Then the AIC is computed as

$$AIC = 2k-2\ln L_{\text{MLE}}$$

This value does not have a true meaning on its own: it only makes sense when compared to the AIC of other models. The idea is that AIC will give information about the following aspects:

  • goodness of fit of the model (indicated by a high likelihood)
  • simplicity of the model (indicated by a small number of predictors): a simpler model is to be preferred over a complex one

The model with the smallest AIC is considered to have the best tradeoff between the two above properties.

In our case, we will iteratively remove a single predictor from the dataset out of the $N=9$ available, creating $N$ nested logistic regression models with $N-1$ predictors each. We will compute the AIC values for all of them and compare the results. In addition, we compute the AIC for the full logistic regression we previously used, and also compare that to the rest of the models.

Ridge Classifier / Least Squares SVM¶

We engage in one last effort to describe the Avila dataset with a linear model by finding a middle ground with SVM-based methods. In the initial steps of our analysis, we inspected the correlation matrix of the dataset and found some slight correlation between certain predictors. We now attempt to model the data with methods that can handle this scenario, in one last attempt to use a linear algorithm in this classification task.

The method we employ is Ridge (Hoerl, 1970): originally designed for regression, this method can be adapted to classification problems. We firstly introduce the algorithm and proceed to explain why it might be useful in our case; we then provide some insight on how it can be interpreted.

Ridge regression original formulation¶

Recall that a linear regression algorithm models target variables as $y=X\beta + \epsilon$. The actual fitted values are $\hat{y}=X\hat{\beta}$, and the vector of coeffiecients $\hat{\beta}$ is found by minimizing the following expression:

$$\hat{\beta}=\arg\min_{\beta}\|y-X\beta\|_2^2=\arg min_{\beta_i}{\sum_i{\left(y_i-\beta_i^Tx_i\right)^2}}$$

Ridge regression performs the same task as above, but uses a penalized version of the minimization problem, i.e. applies a regularization term. The penalty corresponds to the squared sum of all $\beta$'s, except for $\beta_0$ (i.e. the intercept).

\begin{equation}{ \hat{\beta}^{ridge}=\arg\min_{\beta}\|y-X\beta\|_2^2+\lambda\sum_{j=1}^p{\beta_j^2}} \end{equation}

$\beta_0$ is left out of the regularization because there is no sense in "penalizing more" a dataset that has a higher intercept.
In short, Ridge attempts to keep the individual values of the $\beta$'s as low as possible while also tuning them to reasonably fit the data points.

If we assume the data is centered (which it is, in our case), then we can immediately estimate $\beta_0=\bar y=\frac{1}{N}\sum_i y_i$ and take $\beta_0$ out of the $\beta$ vector, along with the column of $1$'s from $X$. This allows to fully write the problem above in vector form:

$$\min_{\beta} \left\| y - {X\beta}\right\|^2_2 + \lambda\|{\beta}\|^2_2$$

Which can be solved analytically: $$\hat{\beta}^{ridge}=\left(X^T X+\lambda I\right)^{-1}X^T y$$

The expression above is mostly the same as the linear regression estimate for $\beta$, except for the added contribution of $\lambda$ to the diagonal of $X^TX$. According to (Hastie, 2009), this makes the overall matrix $X^T X+\lambda I$ nonsingular, even though $X^T X$ itself is not full rank: this eases its invertibility.

In the previous sections, we highlighted how excessive multicollinearity between predictors might lead to numerical instability when computing $X^TX$. Ridge can help in bypassing the issue by slightly modifying $X^TX$ in such a way that makes it more easily invertible (which is the original reason why it was introduced), while also benefitting from the regularization effect.

The hyperparameter $\lambda$ controls the amount of regularization of the model, i.e. how much the $\beta$'s are constrained. In general, as $\lambda$ grows

  • the model variance decreases
  • the model becomes less prone to overfitting
  • model complexity is also reduced (meaning the model may only describe "simpler" phenomena)

Notice that for $\lambda=0$ we again obtain the ordinary least squares estimate for linear regression, while $\lambda\rightarrow+\infty$ yields the null model (all $\beta_i$ but the intercept are set to $0$).

Ridge for classification: least squares SVM¶

Ridge can be extended to binary classifiation scenarios, which can in turn be adapted to multi-class settings via One-vs-One or One-vs-Rest approaches. In this case, Ridge becomes equivalent to a peculiar form of SVM, which we shall briefly discuss.

We label the two classes of the problem with values $-1, +1$. By running a normal Ridge regression on those, we obtain $\hat \beta^{ridge}$ (which includes $\beta_1$, ..., $\beta_p$) and $\hat \beta_0$ which best interpolate the data. The classification rule for a new sample $x_f$ becomes:

  • if $\hat y_f = \hat \beta^T x_f + \beta_0 > 0$, then classify as +1.
  • if $\hat y_f = \hat \beta^T x_f + \beta_0 < 0$, then classify as -1.

This classifier is implemented in scikit-learn's RidgeClassifier class.

This method is also known as Least Squares SVM (Suykens, 1999), which is essentially a non-sparse SVM which uses a square loss (i.e. $(y-f(x))^2$) instead of a hinge loss. The original formulation of a Least Squares SVM is:

$$\min_{w, b, e}\frac{1}{2}\| w\|^2+\frac{\gamma}{2}\sum_i{e_i^2}$$$$\textrm{s.t.}\quad y_i(w^T\phi(x_i)+b)=1-e_i\quad \forall i$$

Because of the equality in the constraints, all points are support vectors, which makes this SVM non-sparse. Setting $f(x):= w^T\phi(x)+b\,$ (where $\phi$ is in this case the identity function, i.e. $\phi(x)=x$) and rewriting the above problem in a unique loss-regularizer expression we get

$$\min_{w}\|w\|^2+\frac{\gamma}{2}\sum_i{\|y_i-f(x_i)\|^2}\iff\min_{w}\|w\|^2+\frac{\gamma}{2}\|y-X\beta\|^2$$

which is equivalent to the original Ridge formulation, for $y_i=\{\pm 1\}$.

PCA and Ridge¶

At the beginning of this section, we remarked how there is some slight correlation between attributes in our dataset, and illustrated how Ridge should be robust against this phenomenon. We now present an alternative way to respond to feature correlation, which can also be used as a means of dimensionality reduction: PCA.

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is an algorithm that has taken on many names and many intepretations within different fields of application; in our case, we see PCA as a preprocessing technique.
Let $X$ be a datset of $n$ rows (samples) and $D$ columns (features). PCA aims to find a matrix $A\in\mathbb{R}^{D\times D}$ which which we can linearly transform the data in a new $n\times D$ matrix $E=XA$. The matrix $E$ should have the following properties:

  1. The $D$ columns of $E$ should be uncorrelated, i.e. have correlation coefficient equal to 0.
  2. Let $\mathbf{e}_i$ for $i=1\dots D$ be the columns of $E$. $\mathbf{e}_1$ shuold have the maximum possible variance, $\mathbf{e}_2$ should have the $2^{nd}$ highest variance, and so on. In other words, each column of $E$ should capture as much information as possible from the data, in descending order.

Beacuse of said properties, PCA can be used as a dimensionality reduction technique by "truncating" the computation of $E$ to its $d^{th}$ column, with $d<D$: we know that these first $d$ columns will capture as much information as possible from the orignal data $X$, discarding the least amount of variance.

We will use PCA to try and muster all available information from the dataset in a few, uncorrelated features. Other than completely removing the slight traces of correlation found during the exploration stage, this will hopefully result in a restricted set of highly "informative" features.

PCA derivation: main ideas¶

We now give a brief insight on the derivation of PCA, without delving too deep into the mathematical details. When deriving PCA, it is assumed that the data $X$ is centered, i.e. that each column of $X$ has had its mean substracted.

$$X:=X - \begin{bmatrix} | & \dots & |\\ \mathbf{\mu}_1 & \dots & \mathbf{\mu}_D\\ | & \dots & | \end{bmatrix}$$

This allows us to write the variance-covariance marix as $S:=\frac{1}{n}X^TX$. It can also be shown that, if $X$ is centered, decorrelation is equivalent to orthogonality, i.e. $\rho_{\mathbf{e}_i, \mathbf{e}_j}=0\iff \mathbf{e}_i^T \mathbf{e}_j = 0$.

Let us assume we want to find $\mathbf{a}_1$, the first column of $A$, with which we can linearly transform the data $X$ and find $\mathbf{e}_1$, the first column of $E$. We also want to respect the two aforementioned PCA conditions. This corresponds to the following optimization problem:

$$\mathbf{a}_1=\arg\max_{\mathbf{a}}\,\text{Var}(\mathbf{e}_1)$$$$\text{s.t.}\quad \mathbf{e}_1 = X\mathbf{a}\quad\text{and}\quad\|\mathbf{a}\|=1$$

Solving this problem, it turns out that $\mathbf{a}_1$ is the (normalized) eigenvector of $S=\frac{1}{n}X^TX$ associated with the highest eigenvalue $\lambda_1$. Moreover, the equality $\lambda_1=\text{Var}(\mathbf{e}_1)$ holds: the eigeinvalue is equal to the variance of the data captured by the first transformed column.

This procudure can be repeated to derive $\mathbf{a}_2$, with the additional decorrelation contstraint of $\mathbf{e}_1^T \mathbf{e}_2=0$. This leads to the conclusion that $\mathbf{a}_2$ is the eigenvector of $S$ associated to the second highest eigenvalue $\lambda_2$, that $\text{Var}\,(\mathbf{e}_2)=\lambda_2$, and so on.

It can be easily shown that the total variance of the columns of $E$ is equal to the total variance of the columns of $X$:

$$\sum_{i=1}^D \text{Var}\,(\mathbf{e}_i) = \sum_{i=1}^D \lambda_i = \text{trace}\,(\mathbf{S}) = \sum_{i=1}^D \text{Var}\,(\,\mathbf{x}_i)$$

Where the first equality holds by construction, the second one by spectral theorem, and the third one by definition of variance-covariance matrix (which has variances on the diagonal).

If we use PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the data from $D$ down to $d$, the amount of information that was retained in the process can be quantified with the explained variance ratio:

$$\text{Explained Variance Ratio} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^d\text{Var}\,(\mathbf{e}_i)}{\sum_{i=1}^D\text{Var}\,(\mathbf{x}_i)}$$

We first inspect how well PCA captures the variance of our dataset by performing it and keeping all components. We then plot the explained variance ratio for each transformed component and its cumulative.

Before moving on to the next section, we discuss some further possible interpretations of Ridge.

Insight: the "hidden" relationship between PCA and Ridge¶

Let us first recap the concepts seen so far. As previously stated, Ridge regression is a linear model in which we infer a set of coefficients $\hat \beta$ by minimizing a $L_2$-regularized square loss function. Said function has a hyperparameter $\lambda$, which controls the regularization strength. For the sake of clarity, let us rename that hyperparameter to $\alpha$. As in any linear model, the fitted data is a linear combination of predictors:

$$\hat y=X\hat\beta^{\,\text{ridge}}=\sum_{i=1}^D x_i\hat\beta_i$$

The Ridge minimization problem has a closed-form solution: $\hat{\beta}^{\,\text{ridge}}=\left(X^T X+\lambda I\right)^{-1}X^T y$. This of course means that

$$\hat y=X\hat \beta^{\,\text{ridge}}=X\left(X^T X+\lambda I\right)^{-1}X^T y$$

On the other hand, PCA is a techinque which allows to transform a dataset $X$ into another dataset $E$ with decorrelated columns $\mathbf{e}_i$ and most of the variance enclosed in the first few columns. Namely, column $\mathbf{e}_i$ has variance $\lambda_i$.

By means of SVD decomposition, it is possible to prove that the fitted values of a Ridge regression inference can be re-written in terms of PCA-transformed predictors. Let $\mathbf{u}_i=\frac{\mathbf{e}_i}{\|\mathbf{e}_i\|}$. Then:

$$\hat y = X\hat{\beta}^{\,\text{ridge}} = \sum_{i=1}^D{\mathbf{u}_i\frac{\lambda_i}{\lambda_i+\alpha\,/n} \mathbf{u}_i^T y}$$

We can verbally describe the meaning of the above expression as follows: $\mathbf{u}_i^T y$ is equivalent to projecting $y$ on $\mathbf{e}_i$ (recall that $\mathbf{u}_i$ is just a normalized $\mathbf{e}_i$). After that projection, we are left with a scalar that we multiply by $\frac{\lambda_i}{\lambda_i+\alpha/n}$. If $\lambda_i \ll \frac{\alpha}{n}$ (i.e. if the variance captured by the $i^{\text{th}}$ transformed component is small), then this scalar will become small. The result is then used as a coefficient for $\mathbf{u}_i$ again, and the linear combination of all $\mathbf{u}_i$'s will form the fitted values $\hat y$.
This means that estimating $\hat y$ with a Ridge regressor is like projecting $y$ on the PCA-transformed components of $X$, shrinking each projection proportionally to the variance captured by that component, and then using the resulting value (let us call it $c_i$) as a coefficient to compute $\hat y$ as a linear combination of the PCA-transformed components (normalized).

$$\hat y=X\hat\beta^{\,\text{ridge}}=\sum_{i=1}^D c_i\mathbf{u}_i$$

In other words, we are still reconstructing the fitted values as a linear combination of the predictors (in a different base), but the coefficients $c_i$ shrink inversely to the amount of variance captured by that predictor. The amount of shrinkage is controlled by the Ridge hyperparameter.

Insight: a bayesian interpretation of Ridge¶

From a statistical standpoint, linear regression models the conditional probability of $y_i$ taking on some value as normally distributed with mean $\beta^T x_i$ and some variance $\sigma$. In other words, $y_i$ is a random variable such that

$$y_i| x_i, \beta \sim \mathcal{N}(\beta^T x_i,\;\sigma^2) \quad\Longrightarrow\quad \mathbb{P}(y_i| x_i, \beta)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}}\exp{-\frac{(y_i- \beta^T x_i)^2}{2\sigma^2}}$$

The equality to the right can be used to compose a likelihood $L(\beta|X, y)$. Giving this problem a Bayesian interpretation, one may choose as prior for each component $\beta_k$ of the vector $\beta$ a set of $\text{i.i.d.}$ normals with mean $0$ and variance $\sigma_0$.

$$\beta_k\overset{iid}{\sim}\mathcal{N}(0, \sigma_0^2)$$

Analytically computing the posterior as $posterior \propto likelihood \cdot prior$ results in

$$ \pi(\beta| X, y) \propto \exp{(-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(\|y-X\beta\|^2 + \frac{\sigma^2}{\sigma^2_0}\sum_{j=1}^p{\beta_j^2}))} $$

Where we can set $\sigma^2/\sigma^2_0 := \lambda$. A MAP point estimation of $\beta$ can be computed by minimizing the negative logarithm of the above expression. This results in the same formulation of the Ridge regression problem as initially illustrated.
In other words, the Ridge regression method can be seen as a MAP of a "bayesian linear regression" in which we use independent normal priors with mean $0$ and variance $\sigma_0^2$ for each $\beta_k$.

K-Nearest-Neighbors¶

It seems as though there is simply no way to linearly model the data distribution: so far, the best results were achieved by an SVM with an RBF kernel. We therefore turn towards an instrinsically non-linear and instrinsically multi-class classification algorithm.

A K-Nearest-Neighbor (kNN) algorithm is typically described in the context of classification, but it is possible to adapt it for regression tasks. It can be applied over any domain $\mathcal{X}$ which allows the computation of a distance metric $d:\mathcal{X} \times \mathcal{X}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^+$.

Let $\pi_i(x)$ be the $i^{\text{th}}$ farthest neighbor from $x$ according to some metric $d$, and let $S=\{(x_i, y_i)\}_i$ be the available training dataset. Then, to classify a new data point $x$:

  • consider $N_k = \{y_i\;\text{associated to}\;\pi_i(x):i\leq k\}$: i.e. the labels of the k nearest neighbors of $x$ accodring to the metric $d$.
  • classify $x$ with the majority label found in the set $N_k$

The most commonly employed metric $d$ is the euclidian distance $d(\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b})=\|\mathbf{a}-\mathbf{b}\|_2$. However, other choices are possible: for example, one could use the Minkowski distance $\left(\sum_{i=1}^D |a_i-b_i|^p\right)^{1/p}$, which introduces a new hyperparameter $p$. For $p=2$, we again obtain the euclidian distance; for $p=1$, the metric becomes the so-called Manhattan distance.

kNN is a relatively "theory-free" algorithm, in the sense that it can be very easily understood and implemented without mathematical jargon. However, theoretical notion should be kept in mind: a kNN will be less effective in data with a high number of features, since points in very high dimensional spaces tend to be more sparse, and distance becomes a less effective instrument for learning tasks.
This is no concern when using the Avila dataset, since it has a relatively low number of predictors.

One furhter aspect should be taken into account when using a kNN:

A too low $k$ may lead to overfitting; a too high $k$ may lead to underfitting.

In particular, in a $1$-NN every point will be able to "claim" at least a small decision region of its own: this will make the overall decision boundaries particularly jagged. Such aspect can be seen both negatively and positively: it might make the model more sensible to noise; on the other hand, it can also be efficient at finding small, outlying clusters of minority classes which are surronded and outnumbered by other bigger clusters of different labels.
This is similar to the condition of our dataset, in which there are some minority classes which, apparently, cannot be easily detected by means of linear models, even with the aid of oversampling techniques.

One last important aspect of the kNN algorithm is the following:

A kNN does not infer any parameter form the data. In this sense, more than an actual model, it can be seen as a heuristic method to guess the label of a test point $x$ given the other points in its proximity. This has the following implications:

  • basically no computation is involved in the training phase, since there is no real training process.
  • the "model" essentially consists in keeping all data points available at any time. In some cases, this might be a burden in terms of memory.
  • at test time, it is necessary to compute the distance of $x_{\text{test}}$ from all points in the dataset

We attempt to apply the usage of a kNN to our classification problem. We perform a gridsearch over different values of $k$ and $p$.
