Decision trees and random forests¶

The last class of algorithms we employ is the Decision Tree. From a conceptual standpoint, it is a relatively simple technique, and has the benefit of a higher interpretability with respect to other algorithms.

A Decision Tree is a classification/regression model which consists in assigning labels to a sample by taking decisions based on the values of its attributes in a hierarchical fashion. More specifically:

  • At each node, a decision is taken based on the truth value of the expression $x_j\leq\theta$, where $x_j$ is some attribute and $\theta$ is threshold value inferred during training.
  • Each leaf of the tree assigns an estimated target value
  • Each leaf corresponds to a "cell" (i.e. a hyper-rectangle) of the input space $\mathcal{X}$. We define an hyper-rectangle as the set of $n$-dimensional points whose values are all contained within certain ranges: $\left\{(x_1\dots x_n): x_j\in[a_j, b_j]\;\forall j\right\}$

The main weakness of a decision tree is its tendency to overfit when grown too much. Because of this, it is necessary to make sure that the growing of the leaves stops at a certain point. We will adress such issue later.
The main problem now is how to actually build a decision tree: a possible option is the ID3 Algorithm.

ID3 algorithm¶

The Iterative Dichotomiser 3 (Quinlan, 1986) is an algorithm to construct a decision tree starting from a dataset $S=\{(x_i, y_i)\}_i$. ID3 can be described as:

  • Greedy: decisions are taken locally according to the best possible split available at the moment.
  • Recursive: at each call of the function ID3(S, Attr) we examine the "gain" that we would achieve by splitting the data on some feature $x_j$; we choose the feature that yields the most gain to split on, and obtain further subsets S_i which we again pass to the function as argument.
  • Categorical (...or not): the original version of this algorithm works only on categorical features. However, it can be generalized to numerical features as well.

In order to formulate the algorithm, we first assume we have some "gain" function $\text{Gain}(S,j)$ which takes a subset of data $S$ and an index $j$ and evaluates how much we can gain from splitting $S$ according to the values of feature $x_j$. This "gain" usually quantifies how well points of different classes are being separated.
The ID3 can then be described by the following pseudocode:

ID3(S, attrs):
   // S: subset of data, attrs: attributes to consider when deciding what to split on
   if all x ∈ S have the same label y:
       return leaf node of label y
   
   if attrs = ∅: // all available attributes have already been used
       return leaf node of label {majority label of S}
   
   j = argmax_i {Gain(S,i)} // find attribute of maximum gain
   for value in x_j:
           T_j = ID3(S[S.x_j == value], attrs.drop(x_j)) //originally, ID3 we splits on each x_j only once
           
   return a decision node which splits on attribute x_j and has T_1 ... T_n as child nodes

While the original ID3 allowed splitting on a certain feature only once, the implementation we use permits to select he same attribute twice for a split in different parts of the tree.

Once the tree is constructed, to infer the label of a new sample $x_f$, we traverse the whole tree according to the conditions found in each node: once we reach a leaf associated to label $y_i$, we assign that label to $x_f$.

Gain and impurity metrics¶

We now need to establish a gain function. The definition of gain is often based on another metric called impurity.

An impurity measure $I$ is computed on a set of samples $S=\{(\mathbf{x}_i, y_i)\}_i$, mostly based on their labels, and possibily with some conitions on their attributes. For example, we may wanto to take into account only the labels whose records have a particular value $a$ on attribute $x_j$ (i.e. only count $y_i : (\mathbf{x}_i)_j=a$).
Intuitively, an impurity function measures how diverse the labels $y_i$ are within a given set $S$. If most labels in $S$ have the same value, then the impurity will be low; instead, if the labels take on several different values, then $S$ will have high impurity.

Let us momentarily assume that we do have some function $I(S)$ that measures the impurity of the set $S$. Of course, when deciding which attribute to split on in a decision tree, we want to pick the attribute that will minimize the impurity of the resulting subsets. We therefore define the gain function of a split as (Shalev-Shwartz, 2014):

$$\text{Gain}(S,j)=I(S)-\sum_{a_k\in x_j}\mathbb{P}(x_j=a_k)\cdot I(S|x_j=a_k)$$

Where $\mathbb{P}(x_j=a_k)$ is defined as the frequency of items with attribute $x_j=a_k$ within $S$: $\mathbb{P}(x_j=a_k):=N_{x_j=a_k}\,/|S|$.
$I(S|x_j=a_k)$ is the impurity of $S$ when taking into account only records with $x_j=a_k$.

The gain of a split essentially measures the difference of impurity level before and after the split. The impurity after the split is determined by the impurity of each subset resulting from the split, weighed on the size of the subset itself.

The only missing aspect is an explicit definition of the impurity measure: there are several possible choices for it, and we are going to illustrate the most popular ones.

Let us define the frequency of occurrence of label $y_i$ inside of set $S$ as $p_{y_i}:=N_{y_i}\,/|S|$.

  • GINI index: $I(S)=1-\sum_{y_i}p_{y_i}^2=\sum_{y_i}p_{y_i}\left(1-p_{y_i}\right)$
  • Entropy: $I(S)=H(S)=-\sum_{y_i}p_{y_i}\log p_{y_i}$
  • Train error: $I(S)=1-\max_{y_i}\{p_{y_i}\}$

In our analysis, we will use the GINI index (the default impurity measure in scikit-learn).

Extending ID3 to numerical features¶

The ID3 we described so far is only able to handle categorical variables. The idea for extending it to numerical features is to take the range of each attribute $x_i$, try to split it according to different thresholds, and select the best one.

To do so, it is sufficient to modify the implementation of the $\text{Gain}$ function according to the following pseudocode:

Gain_improved(S, j):
   // S: set of data, j: index of an attribute found in S
   if x_j is categorical:
       return Gain(S, j)

   for each value a_k ∈ x_j:
       θ <- a_k // set a_k as threshold value
       split S in two sets: {S_l | x_j <= θ} and {S_r | x_j > θ}
       evaluate the impurity of this split as normal
   
   find θ_max that results in the maximum impurity reduction
   return gain of split on θ_max

After checking all features, if $x_j$ turns out to be the most convenient attribute to split on, then the node will split according to the rule $x_j\leq\theta_{max}$. Thus, it will result in two sub-brances.

Overgrowing and overfitting¶

As previously mentioned, a Decision Tree can very easily overfit without imposing any boundary on its depth.
This is because each leaf may end up containing only one training sample, which would result in a too specific classification (i.e. overfitting). For this reason, it is always recommended to set a limit to the tree's growth, which can be expressed in several different ways.

In our case, we will set a limit to the following parameters:

  • maximum depth: limits the maximum length of the path from the root to any leaf. Once that depth is hit by a branch, the current node is transformed into a leaf associated to its current majority label.
  • minimum samples per leaf: sets the minimum amount of items that must be contained in a node for it to become a leaf. If a split would result in any node having fewer items than the minimum quantity, that split cannot be performed.
  • minimum impurity decrease: any split must correspond to a minimum amount of gain in order to be performed. If this does not happen, then the split is not performed. For this evaluation, the gain is weighted on the number of samples contained in the current node over the total number of samples.

We will select the most appropriate values for these hyperparameters via cross validation.

From trees to forests: bootstrapping¶

Decsion trees are fast to train and have a good degree of interpretability, but they often perform badly when compared to other more complex models. This issue is often tackled by using ensemble methods: multiple versions of the same model are trained on different data, and at test time, the output of all models is summarized as one single evaluation. This summarization is often an average of all outputs of the ensemble for each single test item.

The usual way to do so is the bootstrapping technique, whereby it is possible to obtain different versions of the model by slightly varying the training data for each model instance.

When given a dataset $S$, it is possible to simulate the availability of more data by sampling with repetition from $S$. By doing so, we can create any number $B$ of new datasets that are slight variations of $S$. This procedure is known as bootstrapping.

Once we have our $B$ new datasets, we can train $B$ classifiers on those. This is the idea behind the so-called Random Forest model.

A Random Forest (Breiman, 2001) consists of $B$ decision trees trained on $B$ different datasets bootstrapped from the same original dataset $S$. To add further randomness to the tree construction, only a random subset of the available features is considered at each split: usually, for $p$ available features, $\sqrt p$ random features are considered. This helps in making the trees decorrelated, which in turn has the effect of reducing the overall variance of the ensemble (Hastie, 2009).

At test time, a sample $x_f$ is classified by all $B$ trees. To obtain the final label, a majority vote can be performed.
One possible alternative (implemented by scikit-learn) is to have the tree predict probabilities instead of actual labels. Each leaf node is associated to a set of probabilities $\{p_i\}_i$, one for each label. The probability of a label is the fraction of items of that label that falls within that leaf over the total items that fall in that leaf, all at training time: $p_i=N_{y_i}\,/N_{\text{leaf}}$. Then, the output of each decision tree becomes a probability vector, and the ouput of the forest can also be the average probability of each label.

Even in the case of discrete prediction of a label, we can encode it as a one-hot vector to come to a general mathematical summary of the prediction of a boostrap-based ensemble. Let $h_b$ be the predictor trained on the $b^{th}$ boostrapped dataset; then, the decision function of the ensemble is

$$h_{\text{ens}}(x)=\frac{1}{B}\sum_{b=1}^B h_b(x)$$

The advantages of using a random forest instead of a single tree are:

  • an evident increase in accuracy
  • in general, even for models other than trees, the variance of an ensemble is much decreased with respect to one of a single model. This is mathematically true because, by averaging $B$ i.i.d. random variables $\mathcal{Z}_1\dots\mathcal{Z}_B$ of variance $\sigma^2$, we obtain a new random variable of variance $\sigma^2/B$.

We directly employ the Random Forest model. We find the best hyperparameters (among the ones described above) via cross-validation.

Why are trees so effective on Avila?¶

As previously discussed, decision trees have the benefit of being more interpretable than other models. This intepretability is partially lost in an ensemble of hundreds of trees, but we can try to retain some of it by using a metric called Mean Decrease Impurity importance (MDI) (Breiman, 2001). It is, in essence, a weighted average of the impurity that a single feature contributes to decrease throughout the whole forest. It must be computed for each individual feature, and can give an idea of how important that feature is to the model: the higher the value, the higher the relevance.

We have already defined a metric for quantifying a decrease of impurity: the Gain function. Now let us denote as:

  • $t$ a node on some tree, and $N_t$ the number of samples that passed thourgh it at training time
  • $G(t)$ the gain value generated by the split at note $t$
  • $v(t)$ a function which, given a node $t$, returns the attribute that the node was split on
  • $T$ a tree in the forest, and $N_T$ the total number of trees
  • $N$ the size of all bootstrapped datasets
  • $p(t)$ the proportion of samples of the dataset reaching node $t$, computed as $p(t)=N_t\,/N$

Then we define the MDI (i.e. the importance) of a feature $x_j$ as

$$\text{MDI}(x_j)=\frac{1}{N_T}\sum_T\sum_{t\in T\,:\,v(t)=x_j}p(t)G(t)$$

scikit-learn automatically computes this value and normalizes it over all the training features: we can display it visually. We use different colors for page, column and row attributes.

These feature importances are very different from the ones obtained with AIC; but then again, those were computed with Logistc Regression, a radically different model.

At this point, some hypotheses can be made on why a random forest is so effective on the Avila dataset.
With the exception of peak number, the most important features for the model are the ones relative to the whole page and the columns.
Let us now recall that the Avila dataset has a hierarchical structure: for each page, there have two columns; for each column, samples representing 4 rows are taken (De Stefano, 2018). This means that all row samples belonging to the same column will share attributes relative to that column AND page; samples belonging to different columns, but same page, will still share the attributes relative to the page.

This hierarchical structure might be the reason why decision trees work so well on Avila: they too are intrinsically hierarchical, and therefore may be particularly suited to capturing these patterns in the data. By splitting on the "higher level" features, i.e. the ones relative to columns and page, they may be able to conveniently separate several samples from the same class at once, hence achieving an initial major impurity reduction. In this sense, the rows features would play the role of the last subtle details which help in the final, definitive distinction of a scribe from another.

Of course this is not just very ambitious guesswork: all these assumptions are formulated based on the feature importances generated by the random forest, which visibly describe page and column features as the most relevant for the classification task.

For one last validation of the effectiveness of the random forest classifier, we can check the Out-of-Bag error.

Out-of-Bag (OOB) error is an evaluation metric that can be used as a validation technique on bootstrapped classifiers. By definition, a boostrapped dataset is sampled with replacement from the original dataset: hence, there may be samples from the original dataset that do not make it into the boostrapped set. These are called "Out-of-Bag" samples for that specific boostrapped set, and they are not seen during training by the decision tree trained on that set.

OOB error is computed for a sample $\mathbf{x}_i\in S$ by predicting its label with the forest, but only using the trees for which $\mathbf{x}_i$ is an OOB sample. This can be done to check wether the individual models of the enseble are generalizing well to new unseen data.

The OOB error rate can be a way to assess the quality of the model when there is not enough data for holding out a validation set; anyhow, it constitutes a good metric even plenty of data is available.

In scikit-learn, the OOB accuracy is estimated instead of the error rate: the RandomForestClassfier class has a oob_score_ attribute whose value is computed ad $1-\text{OOB error rate}$. Let us check it.

Final evaluation on test set¶

The final step of every data analysis pipeline is the testing phase. Prior to the whole analysis, it is necessary to set aside some data that will never be used, not even for validation: this consitutes a simulation of what the trained models may encounter when used on real data.

One possible approach to the final testing phase would be to just fit the models to the whole training set once, and assess their performance on the test data.

A slightly more elaborate option is to again use bootstrapping to more thoroughly establish not only the accuracy of the model, but also its variance, i.e. how much the model's behavior changes when trained on slightly different sets of data. This value, together with the mean accuracy score, contributes to giving a more complete idea of how trustworthy the model is.

To apply bootstrapping at test time, we do as follows: we create $B$ slightly different training sets by bootstrapping on all the training data. For each bootstrapped set, we train the model on it (applying SMOTE with the proper parameters when necessary) and evaluate the accuracy score of the model on the test set. By doing so, we obtain $B$ different accuracy scores for each model, from which we can compute a mean and a standard deviation.

We perform the operation with $B=5$, print out the results, and illustrate them as a bar chart. Each bar represents the mean accuracy of the model, while the black error bars on top of each bar represent the standard deviation.

In [124]:
# Getting all the final results
final_models = [qda_final, svm_final, final_lr, final_ridge, final_knn, final_forest]
names = ['QDA', 'SVM', 'Logistic Regression', 'Ridge Classifier', 'kNN', 'Random Forest']

n_bootstraps = 5


if exists(final_result_path):
    final_score = pd.read_csv(final_result_path, index_col=0)
else:
    final_score = pd.DataFrame(index=names)

    for i in range(n_bootstraps):
        print(f'Bootstrap {i+1}')
        X_train_boot, y_train_boot = resample(X, y, random_state=i, stratify=y)
        # Save scores in dataframe. Rows: model. Columns: rounds, then mean and std
        scores_boot = pd.Series(index=names)
        for model, name in zip(final_models, names):
            # Logistic reg and ridge need SMOTE on training set. QDA needs two attributes dropped
            if name == 'Logistic Regression':
                print('(Resampling...)', end=' ')
                final_smote = SMOTE(**final_smote_params_lr)
                X_train_boot, y_train_boot = final_smote.fit_resample(X_train_boot, y_train_boot)
            elif name == 'Ridge Classifier':
                print('(Resampling...)', end=' ')
                final_smote = SMOTE(**final_smote_params_ridge)
                X_train_boot, y_train_boot = final_smote.fit_resample(X_train_boot, y_train_boot)
            
            # Training the model (whatever it is) and predicting on test
    
            model.fit(X_train_boot, y_train_boot)
            y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
            score = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
            scores_boot[name] = score
            print(f'\t - {name} scored {score:.3}')

        final_score[f'round_{i}'] = scores_boot
    
    # Save final scores to disk
    final_score.to_csv(final_result_path)

Conclusions¶

All models roughly maintain their validation performance and have relatively low variance. The random forest was not overfitting after all, and it is confirmed to be the most suitable model for this task with a $97\%$ accuracy. kNN and SVM with RBF kernel shortly follow, with $88\%$ and $84\%$ accuracy respectively. This confirms that nonlinear models are more effective on this dataset than linear ones, which all score $61$ to $64\%$ (including SVM with a linear kernel, which did not make it to the final test stage). Despite being technically nonlinear, QDA takes the last place, losing one percentage point of accuracy from the validation score.

Aside from numerical results, it must be pointed out that the data from the test set was also extracted from the Avila bible, and was obtained with the same instrumentation and processed in the same way as the training data. Moreover, test and train set have the same class proportions. Therefore, it is safe to say that the test set closely mirrors the distribution of the training set.
In a scenario in which the samples are extracted from different sources and with different equipment, these results may change drastically: page features may not be as relevant anymore, since the layouts of different tomes may vary. In such case, a different analysis would have to be carried out by giving more relevance to features which are closely related to the scribe's handwriting, such as modular ratio and peak number. This could hurt the performance of the random forest, which seems to heavily rely on page features, and perhaps favor models like logistic regression, which instead appear to favor row-related attributes such as the ones mentioned above.

However, this is all just supposition that would have to be backed up by concrete and more in-depth investigation. This is outside the scope of this dissertation, whose aim was to dissect the Avila dataset as it is, with a rather pedagogic approach. We are satisfied with the results of this analysis and set aside these last assumptions for future work.
